e test should create a migrations directory with files like 1.sql, 2.sql, 10.sql, 11.sql to test numeric ordering edge cases, run the migration runner against a test database, then verify the migrations applied in correct order by checking the _migrations table. This is genuinely an integration-level test since it requires both filesystem and database interaction. The level probabilities would be Unit: 0.25 (sorting function alone), Integration: 0.70 (full pipeline), System: 0.05, with the rest distributed among other levels.\n\nFor preventing re-execution of already-applied migrations, I need to verify state persists across multiple runs. A mocked database might pass if the code calls the right methods, but wouldn't catch real failures like incorrect table queries, wrong column names, or transaction handling that only surface with an actual database schema. The test should run the migration runner against a test database, apply migrations, run it again on the same database, then confirm no migrations re-executed by checking the _migrations table count and verifying idempotent queries show no duplicate effects. This requires integration-level testing with a real database to properly validate state persistence and querying behavior.\n\nFor automatic rollback on failed migrations with no further attempts in the same run, transaction rollback and error handling demand real database transaction semantics. Mocks can simulate transactions without enforcing actual atomicity, and the real failure mode occurs when changes aren't rolled back despite errors or when subsequent migrations still execute after a failure.\n\nThe test involves creating an intentionally failing migration (syntax error or constraint violation), running it against a test database with partial schema, then verifying the failed changes are rolled back with no orphaned tables, the _migrations table doesn't record it, and subsequent migrations don't execute. This requires genuine ACID properties that only 